{"title":"ELK System Deployment","uid":"26db5d13c5993d31674f53301da99963","slug":"ELK-System-Deploy","date":"2021-12-10T15:06:22.000Z","updated":"2021-12-10T15:35:23.363Z","comments":true,"path":"api/articles/ELK-System-Deploy.json","keywords":null,"cover":null,"content":"<h1 id=\"1-Preface\"><a href=\"#1-Preface\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"1. Preface\"></a>1. Preface</h1><p>In the last blog (ELK and Visualization System), we learned that the ELK system is composed of multiple open source applications. Each application needs to run separately, and finally communicate with each other through the corresponding ip address and port (Such as 172.xxx:3000). So if we need to deploy the entire ELK to a cloud server, it is best to deploy each application in a separate cloud server. This not only improves system stability, but also makes it easier to locate errors when problems occur.<br>This deployment method makes it easier for operation and maintenance personnel to maintain and update the system.</p>\n<br>\n\n<h1 id=\"2-System-Topology-Diagram\"><a href=\"#2-System-Topology-Diagram\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"2. System Topology Diagram\"></a>2. System Topology Diagram</h1><p>“image”</p>\n<br>\n\n<h1 id=\"3-Environment-configuration\"><a href=\"#3-Environment-configuration\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"3. Environment configuration\"></a>3. Environment configuration</h1><p>All the files need to be download in <strong>/usr/local/elk</strong> for each cloud server.</p>\n<h2 id=\"3-1-Elasticsearch\"><a href=\"#3-1-Elasticsearch\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"3.1 Elasticsearch\"></a>3.1 Elasticsearch</h2><h3 id=\"3-1-1-Install-Elasticsearch\"><a href=\"#3-1-1-Install-Elasticsearch\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"3.1.1 Install Elasticsearch\"></a>3.1.1 Install Elasticsearch</h3><p>Install the Elasticsearch into <strong>/usr/local/elk</strong></p>\n<blockquote><span class=\"custom-blockquote-svg\"><svg width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"\" xmlns=\"http:/